{"author":{"id":"cc8322a500b8739c77faac347808f6026d9ccb7880d0aaa7ad76754163cd7fdb"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782568927,"nonce":"/tLuveXeD09T/wOK+5A/UDZdo5Y=","kind":"plan","title":"Cranky-Review Remediation + Idempotent Ingest — Implementation Plan"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782568927,"nonce":"PQYKfJK18okKwPDZkaWo36jB5WE=","body":"# Cranky-Review Remediation + Idempotent Ingest — Implementation Plan\n\n\u003e **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Fix every finding in `.test-output/cranky-review-2026-06-17.md` and ship the idempotent marker-based ingest feature designed in `docs/dev/specs/2026-06-17-idempotent-marker-ingest-design.md`.\n\n**Architecture:** Two cohesive tracks in one branch. Track A is mechanical remediation (init adopts an existing repo; safer defaults; CLI/UX polish; docs). Track B is the ingest feature (a `kref-id` trailer marker makes re-ingest idempotent; `kref ingest` takes dirs/multiple paths; the generated hooks use the absolute binary path, merge into an existing `lefthook.yml`, and auto-capture spec-tooling output on commit).\n\n**Tech Stack:** Go 1.26.4, git-bug `entity/dag` v0.10.1, spf13/cobra, Ginkgo v2 + Gomega, lefthook, gitleaks. `task` for build/test/lint.\n\n**Conventions (read before starting):**\n- Tests are **Ginkgo v2 + Gomega only**; one `*_suite_test.go` bootstrap per package; white-box (`package x`) except `internal/entry` specs which are black-box (`package entry_test`).\n- Run unit suites with `task test` (it provisions a pinned gitleaks and wires `KREF_GITLEAKS`); run unit+e2e with `task test:e2e`. Use `MODE=llm` for errors-only.\n- Adding an `entry` operation follows the 4-step recipe in `docs/dev/README.md`.\n- **Decisions already made by the user:** init = *require an existing repo* (adopt it; error if none); default tier = `personal`; v0.1.0 = *reword the README* (do not create a tag); leave `purge`'s repo-wide `git gc` default as-is.\n\n---\n\n## File Structure\n\n| File | Responsibility | Change |\n|---|---|---|\n| `internal/store/store.go` | repo init/open, add/get/list, purge | `Init` adopts existing repo; add `Resolve` (id-prefix), `Update` |\n| `internal/store/store_suite_test.go` | store suite bootstrap | add `gitRepo()` test helper |\n| `internal/entry/operations.go` | dag operations | add `SetTitle` op |\n| `internal/bridge/bridge.go` | file↔entry ingest boundary | marker parse/stamp/strip; D2 state machine; dir walk; multi-path |\n| `internal/bridge/bridge_suite_test.go` | bridge suite bootstrap | add `gitRepo()` test helper |\n| `internal/hooks/hooks.go` | lefthook config | `Render(absKref)`; new `post-commit`; `Merge(existing, generated)` |\n| `cmd/kref/commands.go` | cobra commands | ingest multi-path + `--skip-missing` + array output; default tier `personal`; version template; sync nothing-to-push; purge prompt→stderr; resolve prefixes; hooks install merge + `os.Executable` |\n| `cmd/kref/main.go` | root wiring | `SetVersionTemplate` for `--version` JSON |\n| `cmd/kref/cli_suite_test.go` | cli suite bootstrap | add `gitRepo()` test helper |\n| `test/e2e/e2e_suite_test.go` | e2e harness | `newKrefEnv` git-inits the workdir |\n| `README.md` | user docs | Go floor, default tier, `--body` example, v0.1.0, completion, ingest/hook behavior |\n| `Taskfile.yml` | build/test | gitleaks module path → `gitleaks/gitleaks` |\n| `CHANGELOG.md` | release notes | Unreleased section |\n\n---\n\n# Track A — Mechanical remediation\n\n## Task A1: `kref init` adopts an existing git repo (P0)\n\n**Why:** `store.Init` calls `repository.InitGoGitRepo`, which *creates* a repo and errors if one exists, so the documented Quickstart (`cd your-project \u0026\u0026 kref init`) fails. The user chose **require an existing repo**: adopt it, and error with guidance if the dir is not a git repo.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/store/store.go:34-53`\n- Create helper: `internal/store/store_suite_test.go` (add `gitRepo()`)\n- Modify tests: `internal/store/store_test.go`, `internal/store/sync_test.go`, `internal/bridge/bridge_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Add a `gitRepo()` helper to the store suite**\n\n`internal/store/store_suite_test.go` currently only bootstraps the suite. Append a helper that returns a fresh, already-initialized (non-bare) git repo dir, using go-git directly (no shelling):\n\n```go\npackage store\n\nimport (\n\t\"testing\"\n\n\tgogit \"github.com/go-git/go-git/v5\"\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/ginkgo/v2\"\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/gomega\"\n)\n\nfunc TestStore(t *testing.T) {\n\tRegisterFailHandler(Fail)\n\tRunSpecs(t, \"Store Suite\")\n}\n\n// gitRepo returns a fresh temp dir that is already a (non-bare) git repo,\n// matching how a real user runs `kref init` inside their project.\nfunc gitRepo() string {\n\tGinkgoHelper()\n\tdir := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t_, err := gogit.PlainInit(dir, false)\n\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\treturn dir\n}\n```\n\n(If `store_suite_test.go` already has `TestStore`, keep it and only add the import + `gitRepo`.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Write the failing test for adoption**\n\nAdd to `internal/store/store_test.go`:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"Store init adoption\", func() {\n\tIt(\"adopts an existing git repo\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\ts, err := Init(dir, \"Tester\", \"tester@example.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = s.Close() })\n\t\tid, err := s.Add(entry.TierShared, \"spec\", \"T\", \"b\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(id.String()).NotTo(BeEmpty())\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"errors with guidance when the dir is not a git repo\", func() {\n\t\tdir := GinkgoT().TempDir() // NOT a git repo\n\t\t_, err := Init(dir, \"Tester\", \"tester@example.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).To(MatchError(ContainSubstring(\"not a git repository\")))\n\t\tExpect(err).To(MatchError(ContainSubstring(\"git init\")))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Run it — verify it fails**\n\nRun: `task test -- ./internal/store/ 2\u003e/dev/null || go test ./internal/store/`\nExpected: FAIL — the \"errors with guidance\" case fails because `Init` currently *creates* the repo (no error), and the \"adopts\" case fails because `InitGoGitRepo` errors on the existing `.git`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Rewrite `store.Init` to adopt-or-error**\n\nReplace `internal/store/store.go:34-53` with:\n\n```go\n// Init bootstraps kref inside an EXISTING git repository at dir: it opens the\n// repo, creates an author identity, and persists it as the repo user. The\n// repository must already exist (run `git init` first) — kref stores its\n// knowledge in the repo whose history you want it to travel with, so it never\n// creates a throwaway repo of its own.\nfunc Init(dir, name, email string) (*Store, error) {\n\tclean := filepath.Clean(dir)\n\t// Require an existing git repo. git-bug's OpenGoGitRepo searches upward for\n\t// .git but reports \"no repo\" with a non-sentinel error, so pre-check with\n\t// go-git's PlainOpenWithOptions (same upward search) for a reliable sentinel.\n\tif _, err := gogit.PlainOpenWithOptions(clean, \u0026gogit.PlainOpenOptions{DetectDotGit: true}); err != nil {\n\t\tif errors.Is(err, gogit.ErrRepositoryNotExists) {\n\t\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"%s is not a git repository — run `git init` first, then `kref init`\", clean)\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\trepo, err := repository.OpenGoGitRepo(clean, localStorageNamespace, clockLoaders())\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\tauthor, err := newAuthor(repo, name, email)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\tif err := author.Commit(repo); err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\t// Persist this identity as the repo's user so Open() reloads the SAME\n\t// (committed, resolvable) identity rather than minting a fresh one.\n\tif err := identity.SetUserIdentity(repo, author); err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\treturn \u0026Store{repo: repo, author: author, dir: clean}, nil\n}\n```\n\nAdd the imports to the `import` block in `store.go`:\n\n```go\n\t\"errors\"\n\n\tgogit \"github.com/go-git/go-git/v5\"\n```\n\n**Verified APIs (2026-06-18):** `gogit.ErrRepositoryNotExists` is a sentinel\n(`errors.New(\"repository does not exist\")`); `PlainOpenWithOptions(path,\n\u0026PlainOpenOptions{DetectDotGit: true})` returns it when no `.git` is found\nwalking up from `clean` (go-git v5.17.1 `repository.go`/`options.go`). `go mod\ntidy` promotes `github.com/go-git/go-git/v5` from indirect to direct — add that\nto the Task A1 commit (`git add go.mod go.sum`).\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Update the remaining empty-dir call sites in store tests**\n\nIn `internal/store/store_test.go` and `internal/store/sync_test.go`, every `dir := GinkgoT().TempDir()` (or inline `GinkgoT().TempDir()`) that is immediately passed to `Init(...)` must become `gitRepo()`. Mechanical replacements:\n- `dir := GinkgoT().TempDir()` → `dir := gitRepo()` (only where `dir` feeds `Init`)\n- `Init(GinkgoT().TempDir(), ...)` → `Init(gitRepo(), ...)`\n\nDo NOT change `dir := GinkgoT().TempDir()` in the new \"errors with guidance\" test (it must stay a non-repo).\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Run the store suite — verify it passes**\n\nRun: `go test ./internal/store/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 7: Fix the bridge tests the same way**\n\n`internal/bridge/bridge_test.go` calls `store.Init(dir, ...)` on `GinkgoT().TempDir()` twice. Add a `gitRepo()` helper to `internal/bridge/bridge_suite_test.go` (same body as Step 1 but `package bridge`), and change the two `dir := GinkgoT().TempDir()` lines that feed `store.Init` to `dir := gitRepo()`. Leave the `EnsureGitignore` test's temp dir alone (it doesn't init a store).\n\nRun: `go test ./internal/bridge/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 8: Fix the cmd/kref cli_test init sites**\n\nThe P0 change also breaks `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`, whose specs `init` on bare temp dirs. Add a `gitRepo()` helper to `cmd/kref/cli_suite_test.go` (same body as Step 1 but `package main`, importing `gogit \"github.com/go-git/go-git/v5\"`). Then in `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`, change **every** `dir := GinkgoT().TempDir()` (and `dirA`/`dirB := GinkgoT().TempDir()`) that is followed by a `run(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", …)` to use `gitRepo()` instead. Leave temp dirs that are NOT init'd (e.g. the `hooks install` spec at ~line 152, which only writes `lefthook.yml` and opens no store) as `GinkgoT().TempDir()`.\n\nRun: `go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 9: Tidy modules and commit**\n\nRun: `go mod tidy \u0026\u0026 go build ./...`\nExpected: clean (`go-git/v5` is now direct in `go.mod`).\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/store/store.go internal/store/store_suite_test.go internal/store/store_test.go internal/store/sync_test.go internal/bridge/bridge_suite_test.go internal/bridge/bridge_test.go cmd/kref/cli_suite_test.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go go.mod go.sum\ngit commit -m \"fix: kref init adopts an existing git repo (P0)\"\n```\n\n## Task A2: e2e harness git-inits the workdir; add the P0 regression spec\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `test/e2e/e2e_suite_test.go:56-63`\n- Modify: `test/e2e/kref_e2e_test.go` (add a Describe)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Make `newKrefEnv` create a git repo in the workdir**\n\nIn `test/e2e/e2e_suite_test.go`, replace the return line of `newKrefEnv` so the work dir is a real git repo before kref runs. Change:\n\n```go\n\treturn \u0026krefEnv{home: home, dir: GinkgoT().TempDir()}\n```\n\nto:\n\n```go\n\tdir := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\tgi := exec.Command(\"git\", \"init\", dir)\n\tgi.Env = []string{\"HOME=\" + home, \"GIT_CONFIG_NOSYSTEM=1\", \"PATH=\" + os.Getenv(\"PATH\")}\n\tout, err := gi.CombinedOutput()\n\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred(), \"git init workdir: %s\", string(out))\n\treturn \u0026krefEnv{home: home, dir: dir}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Add the P0 regression spec**\n\nAppend to `test/e2e/kref_e2e_test.go`:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"init in a git repo\", func() {\n\tIt(\"adopts an existing repo and refuses a non-git dir\", func() {\n\t\te := newKrefEnv(\"Repo Adopter\", \"adopt@example.com\")\n\t\t// newKrefEnv already `git init`-ed e.dir; init must now succeed.\n\t\tout := e.mustRun(\"init\")\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"initialized\"))\n\n\t\t// A sibling dir that is NOT a git repo must fail with guidance.\n\t\tbare := GinkgoT().TempDir()\n\t\tfull := []string{\"--dir\", bare, \"init\"}\n\t\tcmd := exec.Command(krefBin, full...)\n\t\tcmd.Env = e.osEnv()\n\t\tvar sout, serr bytes.Buffer\n\t\tcmd.Stdout, cmd.Stderr = \u0026sout, \u0026serr\n\t\terr := cmd.Run()\n\t\tExpect(err).To(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(serr.String()).To(ContainSubstring(\"git init\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Run e2e — verify pass**\n\nRun: `task test:e2e -- ./test/e2e/ 2\u003e/dev/null || go test -tags e2e ./test/e2e/`\nExpected: PASS (all existing specs still init successfully because the workdir is now a repo; the new spec passes).\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add test/e2e/e2e_suite_test.go test/e2e/kref_e2e_test.go\ngit commit -m \"test(e2e): git init the workdir; assert init adopts/refuses (P0)\"\n```\n\n## Task A3: Default tier → `personal` (P1)\n\n**Why:** `kref add`/`kref ingest` default to `shared` (the team-syncable tier). The user chose `personal`.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go:100` and `cmd/kref/commands.go:128`\n- Check: tests asserting a default tier\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Find tests asserting the default tier**\n\nRun: `grep -rn '\"shared\"\\|TierShared' cmd/kref/cli_test.go test/e2e/kref_e2e_test.go`\nFor any case that adds/ingests **without** `--tier` and then asserts `shared`, change the expected value to `personal`. (Cases that pass `--tier shared` explicitly stay.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Change the defaults**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/commands.go`, both flag registrations:\n\n```go\n\tc.Flags().StringVar(\u0026tier, \"tier\", \"personal\", \"tier: private|personal|shared\")\n```\n\n(one in `newAddCmd`, one in `newIngestCmd`).\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Run cli + e2e**\n\nRun: `go test ./cmd/kref/ \u0026\u0026 go test -tags e2e ./test/e2e/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/commands.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go test/e2e/kref_e2e_test.go\ngit commit -m \"fix: default tier is personal, not shared (P1)\"\n```\n\n## Task A4: Unify `kref version` and `kref --version` (P2)\n\n**Why:** `kref version` emits JSON; `kref --version` emits `kref version \u003cv\u003e`. Make `--version` emit the same JSON.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/main.go:13-37`\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd to `cmd/kref/cli_test.go` (uses the existing `run` helper that captures stdout):\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"version output\", func() {\n\tIt(\"emits identical JSON for `version` and `--version`\", func() {\n\t\tsub := run(\"version\")\n\t\tflag := run(\"--version\")\n\t\tExpect(flag).To(Equal(sub))\n\t\tExpect(flag).To(ContainSubstring(`\"version\"`))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n(If `run` does not already return stdout as a string, mirror the existing helper used by the other cli specs in this file.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run — verify fail**\n\nRun: `go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI`\nExpected: FAIL — `--version` prints `kref version \u003cv\u003e`, not JSON.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Set a JSON version template**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/main.go`, inside `newRootCmd` after the `root` literal is created, add:\n\n```go\n\troot.SetVersionTemplate(\"{\\n  \\\"version\\\": \\\"{{.Version}}\\\"\\n}\\n\")\n```\n\nThis matches `writeJSON`'s 2-space-indented single-key object exactly.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run — verify pass**\n\nRun: `go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/main.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"fix: kref --version emits the same JSON as kref version (P2)\"\n```\n\n## Task A5: `sync push`/`pull` report `nothing-to-push` when no tier is syncable (P2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go:279-306` (`runSync`)\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"sync with no remotes\", func() {\n\tIt(\"reports nothing-to-push rather than pushed\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", \"--name\", \"T\", \"--email\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\tout := run(\"--dir\", dir, \"sync\", \"push\")\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"nothing-to-push\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).NotTo(ContainSubstring(`\"pushed\"`))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n(The `gitRepo()` helper was added to `cmd/kref/cli_suite_test.go` in Task A1 Step 8 — reuse it.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run — verify fail**\n\nRun: `go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: FAIL — current output is `{\"status\":\"pushed\",\"tiers\":[]}`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Make the verb conditional on work done**\n\nIn `runSync`, change the final return so an empty `done` reports a distinct status. Replace:\n\n```go\n\treturn writeJSON(cmd, map[string]any{\"status\": verb, \"tiers\": done})\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```go\n\tstatus := verb\n\tif len(done) == 0 {\n\t\tstatus = \"nothing-to-\" + strings.TrimSuffix(verb, \"ed\") // pushed→push, pulled→pull\n\t}\n\treturn writeJSON(cmd, map[string]any{\"status\": status, \"tiers\": done})\n```\n\n`strings` is already imported in `commands.go`. (`pushed`→`nothing-to-push`, `pulled`→`nothing-to-pull`.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run — verify pass**\n\nRun: `go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/commands.go cmd/kref/cli_suite_test.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"fix: sync reports nothing-to-push/pull when no tier has a remote (P2)\"\n```\n\n## Task A6: `purge` confirmation prompt goes to stderr (P2)\n\n**Why:** the prompt is interleaved with the JSON result on stdout, so stdout is not machine-parseable.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go:361-386` (`confirmPurge`)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing e2e assertion**\n\nAdd to `test/e2e/kref_e2e_test.go` (the e2e harness separates stdout/stderr):\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"purge prompt stream\", func() {\n\tIt(\"writes the confirmation to stderr, leaving stdout pure JSON\", func() {\n\t\te := newKrefEnv(\"Purger\", \"p@example.com\")\n\t\te.mustRun(\"init\")\n\t\tid := idOf(e.mustRun(\"add\", \"--title\", \"doomed\"))\n\t\tstdout, stderr, _ := e.run(\"n\\n\", \"purge\", id)\n\t\tExpect(stderr).To(ContainSubstring(\"About to PURGE\"))\n\t\tExpect(stdout).NotTo(ContainSubstring(\"About to PURGE\"))\n\t\tExpect(stdout).To(ContainSubstring(\"aborted\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run — verify fail**\n\nRun: `go test -tags e2e ./test/e2e/ -run TestE2E`\nExpected: FAIL — the prompt is currently on stdout.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Send the prompt to stderr**\n\nIn `confirmPurge`, change the first line from:\n\n```go\n\tout := cmd.OutOrStdout()\n```\n\nto:\n\n```go\n\tout := cmd.ErrOrStderr()\n```\n\nThe stdin read stays `cmd.InOrStdin()`. The `aborted`/`purged` JSON result (written by the caller via `writeJSON`) remains on stdout.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run — verify pass**\n\nRun: `go test -tags e2e ./test/e2e/ -run TestE2E`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/commands.go test/e2e/kref_e2e_test.go\ngit commit -m \"fix: purge prompt writes to stderr, keeping stdout machine-parseable (P2)\"\n```\n\n## Task A7: Accept id prefixes; tier-agnostic not-found error (P2)\n\n**Why:** `kref show ad1a3d16` fails with `read ad1a3d16 in tier private: invalid id: invalid length` — no prefix matching, and the error leaks the internal tier loop.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/store/store.go` (add `Resolve`)\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go` (`show`, `rm`, `purge` resolve first)\n- Test: `internal/store/store_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"Store id resolution\", func() {\n\tIt(\"resolves an unambiguous hex prefix to the full id\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\ts, err := Init(dir, \"T\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = s.Close() })\n\t\tid, err := s.Add(entry.TierShared, \"spec\", \"Prefixed\", \"b\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\n\t\tgot, err := s.Resolve(id.String()[:8])\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(got).To(Equal(id))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"returns a tier-agnostic not-found for an unknown prefix\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\ts, err := Init(dir, \"T\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = s.Close() })\n\t\t_, err = s.Resolve(\"deadbeef\")\n\t\tExpect(err).To(MatchError(ContainSubstring(\"not found\")))\n\t\tExpect(err.Error()).NotTo(ContainSubstring(\"tier\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run — verify fail**\n\nRun: `go test ./internal/store/`\nExpected: FAIL — `Resolve` undefined.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Implement `Resolve`**\n\nAdd to `internal/store/store.go` (and add `\"github.com/git-bug/git-bug/entity/dag\"` is already imported):\n\n```go\n// Resolve expands a full id or an unambiguous hex prefix to a stored entry id,\n// searching every tier. The not-found and ambiguous errors never name a tier —\n// callers see one entry space, not kref's internal per-tier loop.\nfunc (s *Store) Resolve(prefix string) (entity.Id, error) {\n\tif prefix == \"\" {\n\t\treturn \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"empty id\")\n\t}\n\tvar matches []entity.Id\n\tseen := map[entity.Id]bool{}\n\tfor _, t := range entry.AllTiers() {\n\t\tids, err := dag.ListLocalIds(entry.Definition(t), s.repo)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\treturn \"\", err\n\t\t}\n\t\tfor _, id := range ids {\n\t\t\tif id.HasPrefix(prefix) \u0026\u0026 !seen[id] {\n\t\t\t\tseen[id] = true\n\t\t\t\tmatches = append(matches, id)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\tswitch len(matches) {\n\tcase 0:\n\t\treturn \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"entry %s not found\", prefix)\n\tcase 1:\n\t\treturn matches[0], nil\n\tdefault:\n\t\treturn \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"id prefix %s is ambiguous (%d matches)\", prefix, len(matches))\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run — verify pass**\n\nRun: `go test ./internal/store/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Resolve prefixes in the CLI**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/commands.go`, the `show`, `rm`, and `purge` commands currently do `idFromArg(args[0])`. Change each to resolve first. For `show`:\n\n```go\n\t\t\ts, err := store.Open(*dir)\n\t\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\tdefer s.Close()\n\t\t\tid, err := s.Resolve(args[0])\n\t\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\tsnap, err := s.Get(id)\n```\n\nApply the same `id, err := s.Resolve(args[0])` pattern in `rm` (then `s.Tombstone(id)`) and `purge` (then `s.Get(id)` / `s.Purge(id, ...)`). The `rm` and `purge` JSON results currently echo `args[0]`; change them to echo `id.String()` so the output shows the resolved id. `idFromArg` is now unused — delete it.\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Run cli + e2e**\n\nRun: `go test ./cmd/kref/ \u0026\u0026 go test -tags e2e ./test/e2e/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 7: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/store/store.go cmd/kref/commands.go internal/store/store_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat: accept git-style id prefixes; tier-agnostic not-found (P2)\"\n```\n\n## Task A8: README, Taskfile, CHANGELOG doc fixes (P1/P2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `README.md`, `Taskfile.yml`, `CHANGELOG.md`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Correct the Go prerequisite (P1, README.md:38)**\n\nReplace:\n\n```\n`kref` is a Go program. You need **Go ≥ 1.25** to build it, and the **gitleaks**\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```\n`kref` is a Go program. You need **Go ≥ 1.26.4** to build it (or any Go with\n`GOTOOLCHAIN=auto`, which fetches the 1.26.4 toolchain over the network on the\nfirst build — `task build` sets this for you). It also needs the **gitleaks**\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Fix the `--body` example so it does not store a literal `\\n` (P2, README.md:61)**\n\nReplace the `kref add` Quickstart line:\n\n```\nkref add --title \"Auth design\" --kind spec --body \"# Auth\\